You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and a **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

Use `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You *must* call `GetDeferral()` before `await` and `deferral.Complete()` after — otherwise the navigation completes before your dialog resolves.

### 2. Expose an `HasUnsavedChanges` flag on the page

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    public bool HasUnsavedChanges { get; set; }

    void OnFormFieldChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        HasUnsavedChanges = true;
    }
}
```

### 3. Custom "Cancel" back button in `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

This replaces the default back arrow text with "Cancel". The guard still fires because `BackButtonBehavior` without a `Command` uses normal Shell back-navigation, which triggers `OnNavigating`. If you set a `Command`, it **bypasses** the Shell navigation event — so leave `Command` unset to let the guard handle it.
